{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492766"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1151"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1151"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.08,0.46,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111250"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1151"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"652"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111250"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right leg pain and swelling. The pain involves the whole leg and worsens when standing. She was diagnosed with rectal adenocarcinoma two weeks ago and has not yet undergone surgery or commenced treatment; she is scheduled to start neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy in the coming month. She had a deep vein thrombosis during pregnancy at age 30. She has no other significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke and works as a teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. The right leg is swollen to the mid-thigh with pitting oedema and calf tenderness; there is no erythema or increased warmth. Peripheral pulses are palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a duplex ultrasound showing an occlusive thrombus in the right common femoral vein. Urea 5.1 mmol/L (2.5-7.8), creatinine 66 \u00b5mol/L (45-90), estimated glomerular filtration rate 90 mL/min/1.73 m2 (\u226560).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate anticoagulant choice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apixaban","Rivaroxaban","Enoxaparin","Warfarin","Dabigatran"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer-associated thrombosis management must weigh recurrence risk, bleeding risk from tumour-related mucosal disease, timing of procedures, and drug interactions with systemic therapy. This patient has newly diagnosed, unoperated rectal cancer with impending surgery and chemoradiotherapy. In untreated gastrointestinal malignancy, low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) is preferred as initial therapy because it has a lower risk of gastrointestinal mucosal bleeding than direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is effective for cancer-associated thrombosis but should be used cautiously in untreated gastrointestinal cancer due to higher mucosal bleeding risk; in an unoperated rectal cancer, it is not preferred as initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E carries similar concerns to apixaban with respect to bleeding risk in unoperated gastrointestinal cancers, and is therefore less suitable as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended as initial treatment in people with active, untreated gastrointestinal malignancy. It reduces recurrence compared with warfarin, accommodates upcoming procedures, and is associated with lower mucosal bleeding risk than some direct oral anticoagulants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is generally avoided in active cancer because of higher venous thromboembolism recurrence compared with LMWH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E is not preferred as it has limited evidence in cancer-associated thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In people with active, untreated gastrointestinal cancer and deep vein thrombosis, initial anticoagulation with LMWH is preferred due to the lower bleeding risk.","DOACs should be avoided or used cautiously in untreated gastrointestinal or genitourinary cancers because of a higher risk of mucosal bleeding.","Warfarin is generally avoided in cancer-associated thrombosis due to higher recurrence rates compared to LMWH."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Therapeutic Guidelines: Venous thromboembolism (VTE) treatment [Internet]. Melbourne (Australia): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2023 Jun [amended 2024 Jul; cited 2025 Aug 11]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1151"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-11T20:19:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T20:20:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"